[[File:Hairs of Loganiaceae EP-IV2-012.png|thumb|right|Several hair types occur on plants of Loganiaceae, including multicellular secretory colleters shown here in cross-section (C, D, H).]]

'''Colleters''' are [[plant]] structures, multicellular secretory [[trichome|hairs]], found in groups near the base of [[Petiole (botany)|petioles]], on [[stipule]]s, and on [[sepal]]s.  They are found in members of the [[Loganiaceae]] and [[Rubiaceae]] families.<ref>{{citation |author1=Klein, D.E. |author2=Moreira Gomes, V. |author3=Da Silva-Neto, S.J. |author4=Da Cunha, M. |year=2004 |title=The Structure of Colleters in Several Species of ''Simira'' (Rubiaceae) |journal=Annals of Botany |volume=94 |issue=5 |pages=733–740 |url=http://aob.oxfordjournals.org/content/94/5/733.abstract |doi=10.1093/aob/mch198 |pmid=15374836 |pmc=4242219}}</ref><ref>{{citation |author1=Hickey, M. |author2=King, C. |year=2001  |title=The Cambridge Illustrated Glossary of Botanical Terms |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>

